The PES University was not a very popular name back then.  Now, the tables have turned and the whole name itself is quite the talk of most of the college going youngsters. Recently, I had been to this place with our school students to participate in some of the events conducted by the University for the whole of Bangalore and neighbouring states. The Amateur Scientist.  It was conducted on a large scale. Over 10,000 children from different schools had attended this event. Initially, we found it difficult to gain entry. Thanks to the CEO of the University who really initiated all the arrangements and organised the events and all the teachers had a comfortable day in the University. I would like to give a detailed review on this college, for all current and prospective students. I advise you to read this carefully, as it's nothing but the truth, and shall be agreed upon by most students. I passed out this year, and I was waiting for an opportunity to share my experience with this '"University"without fearing for any implications.  1. First of all, it's not a ''College'' or ''University''. It's a coaching institute, in crude words. There is zero interest from the authorities to promote co-curriculars or extra activites for the students. The college's tryst with a student begins at 8:15 and ends at 3:30 everyday, without fail.   2. Students are like a herd of goats, who think their world is limited to only till the compound walls of the college. No one talks about research, contributing to the society or further studies. Everyone is interested in getting a job from Infosys, Wipro and Accenture and consider it to be a ''Great'' thing if they achieve so.  3. The environment is highly, mind you, HIGHLY regional/racial. North Indians are discriminated against the local South Indian guys in unexplainable degree. For example, the erstwhile HoD of Civil Engg in this college told our class that ''All problems in Bangalore are because of you North Indians'' when he asked some question regarding a topic. Another example is that if you are a South Indian, your vehicle is more likely to be allowed inside the campus and if you're from the North, you're immediately asked to back off.  4. The hostel is a nightmare. Perhaps an ISIS run Girls Hostel will have lesser regulations and norms than the PES Boys' Hostel. The Hostel staff and guards dominate the students completely and un-necessary harass them at any opportunity. The Food is a nightmare and so is the overall hostel environment, where no is allowed to wear shorts. How ancient can some people be?  5. Coming to the administration, all they care about is money. Don't expect any help or leniency from them. The PESU Vice Chancellor and the PESU Controller of Exams are the kingpins here. Even if you fail a subject by a mark, you won't be given any sort of grace, else the college loses it's 1 subject summer term fees that you'll ultimately have to pay.  6. The security guards bark orders at the students. Student morale and self esteem is EXTINCT. The low level staff think of themselves as a industrialist and demand to be addressed as 'Sir' or ''Madam'. If you refused to be harassed by them, you perish.  7. The college segregates good and weak students. Weak students are left behind like garbage whereas good students are lured with incentives and money, by offering bogus scholarships and other things.  8. There is ZERO financial support from the college when it comes to organising or participating in an event. I was part of the automobile designing group of the college and the college showed no interest in financially or emotionally supporting us. However, when we succeeded and our name came in the newspapers, D Jawahar (apparently the pro-chancellor of the college) ran with all his might to get the college logo and name pasted on our certificates and erected banners outside the main gate. Such are the double standards.  In short, looking back at my 4 year term there, it was nothing short of a NIGHTMARE. The college is a association of anarchists, as simple as that, where the student has ZERO respect, affection or encouragement to succeed in life.  Disclaimer : I am an individual. No rival college or newspaper paid me to write this review, because the brilliant authorities of PES will surely think so. I also know that the so called geniuses of PES's Computer Science Department will try their best to get this review removed. But don't worry guys, I have already taken a screenshot of this and have posted it on many other forums.   All the best tormenting future students. I just wish Google had a Zero Star Rating for PESU/PESIT.
